{"title_page": "Peter Maurer", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n[[File:ICRC president Peter Maurer in Syria (7930973296).jpg|thumb|Peter Maurer during a three-day mission in [[Syria]], in September 2012.]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets with President of the Red Cross Maurer in New York City (44927001472).jpg|thumb|Maurer (left) meets with US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] (right) in 2018]]\n\n'''Peter Maurer''' (born 1956) is the President of the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] (ICRC),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icrc.org/en/document/president-and-vice-president-icrc |title=The president and vice-president of the ICRC |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2015}}</ref> appointed 1 July 2012. Maurer was born in [[Thun]], [[Switzerland]].\n\n==Education==\nMaurer studied History and International Law in Berne, and was awarded a PhD.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1987, Maurer entered the Swiss Diplomatic Service ([[Federal Department of Foreign Affairs]]), where he held various positions in Berne and Pretoria, before being transferred to New York in 1996 as Deputy Permanent Observer at the Swiss Mission to the [[United Nations]]. In 2000, he was appointed Ambassador and head of the division in charge of human security at the headquarters of Switzerland's Foreign Ministry in Berne.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icrc.org/eng/resources/documents/news-release/2011/geneva-news-2011-10-19.htm |title=ICRC names new president |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Maurer was appointed Ambassador and Permanent Representative of Switzerland to the United Nations in New York. In this position, he endeavoured to integrate Switzerland, which had only recently joined the United Nations, into multilateral networks. In June 2009, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] elected Maurer Chairman of the [[United Nations General Assembly Fifth Committee|Fifth Committee]], in charge of United Nations administrative and budgetary affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2009/bio4129.doc.htm |title=Peter Maurer of Switzerland Chair of Fifth Committee |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2009}}</ref> In addition, he was elected Chairman of the Burundi Configuration of the [[Peacebuilding Commission|UN Peacebuilding Commission]]. In January 2010, Maurer became Switzerland's State Secretary for Foreign Affairs, a position he held until he was elected President of the ICRC.\n\nSince 2012, Maurer has led the ICRC through a historic budget increase, from 1.1 billion CHF in 2011 to over 1.6 billion CHF in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icrc.org/en/who-we-are/finances |title=ICRC Finances |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2015}}</ref> In addition, he launched the world\u2019s first \u201chumanitarian impact bond\u201d scheme, in which private investors lend \u20ac22 million of five-year funding and their repayments depend on what difference the project makes to its clients\u2019 lives.<ref>Kate Allen (September 8, 2017) [https://www.ft.com/content/8d82241d-096b-313e-91d8-786ba99d2073 Red Cross launches \u201chumanitarian impact bond\u201d] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref> Since 2019, Maurer has been co-chairing the [[World Economic Forum]] High-Level Group on Humanitarian Investing, alongside [[B\u00f8rge Brende]] and [[Kristalina Georgieva]].<ref>[https://www.weforum.org/press/2019/01/world-economic-forum-2019-annual-meeting-launching-a-new-humanitarian-investing-initiative/ World Economic Forum 2019 Annual Meeting launching a new Humanitarian Investing Initiative] [[World Economic Forum]], press release of January 18, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* [[International Gender Champions]] (IGC), Member (since 2017)<ref>[https://genderchampions.com/champions Members] [[International Gender Champions]] (IGC).</ref>\n* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Member of the Board (since 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weforum.org/news/peter-maurer-joins-foundation-board-world-economic-forum |title=Peter Maurer Joins Foundation Board, World Economic Forum |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104114218/http://www.weforum.org/news/peter-maurer-joins-foundation-board-world-economic-forum |archivedate=4 November 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Co-Chair of the Global Future Council on the Future of the Humanitarian System<ref>[https://www.weforum.org/communities/the-future-of-the-humanitarian-system Global Future Council: The Future of the Humanitarian System] [[World Economic Forum]].</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 2014 \u2013 Honorary doctorate, [[University of Basel]]<ref>[https://www.unibas.ch/en/News-Events/News/Uni-Info/Dies-Academicus-2014-at-the-University-of-Basel--Honorary-Doctorate-for-ICRC-President-Peter-Maurer.html Dies Academicus 2014 at the University of Basel: Honorary Doctorate for ICRC President Peter Maurer] [[University of Basel]], press release of November 28, 2014.</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 Honorary doctorate, [[Waseda University]]<ref>[https://www.waseda.jp/top/en-news/62682 Honorary Doctorate Conferred on Dr. Peter Maurer, President of the International Committee of the Red Cross] [[Waseda University]], press release of December 7, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaurer is married and is the father of two children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n* UN, 15 September 2009. [https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2009/bio4129.doc.htm PETER MAURER OF SWITZERLAND CHAIR OF FIFTH COMMITTEE]\n* ICRC, 19 October 2011. [http://www.icrc.org/eng/resources/documents/news-release/2011/geneva-news-2011-10-19.htm ICRC names new president]\n* ICRC, 7 September 2012. [http://www.icrc.org/eng/resources/documents/news-release/2012/syria-news-2012-09-07.htm Syria: ICRC president concludes visit amid relentless fighting]\n* WEF, 3 November 2014. [https://web.archive.org/web/20141104114218/http://www.weforum.org/news/peter-maurer-joins-foundation-board-world-economic-forum Peter Maurer Joins Foundation Board, World Economic Forum]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Peter Maurer}}\n* [https://www.icrc.org/en/person/peter-maurer The president of the ICRC]\n\n{{Portal bar|Switzerland|Biography}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maurer, Peter}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Red Cross personnel]]\n[[Category:People from Thun]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n[[File:ICRC president Peter Maurer in Syria (7930973296).jpg|thumb|Peter Maurer during a three-day mission in [[Syria]], in September 2012.]]\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets with President of the Red Cross Maurer in New York City (44927001472).jpg|thumb|Maurer (left) meets with US Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] (right) in 2018]]\n\n'''Peter Maurer''' (born 1956) is the President of the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]] (ICRC),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icrc.org/en/document/president-and-vice-president-icrc |title=The president and vice-president of the ICRC |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2015}}</ref> appointed 1 July 2012. Maurer was born in [[Thun]], [[Switzerland]].\n\n==Education==\nMaurer studied History and International Law in Berne, and was awarded a PhD.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1987, Maurer entered the Swiss Diplomatic Service ([[Federal Department of Foreign Affairs]]), where he held various positions in Berne and Pretoria, before being transferred to New York in 1996 as Deputy Permanent Observer at the Swiss Mission to the [[United Nations]]. In 2000, he was appointed Ambassador and head of the division in charge of human security at the headquarters of Switzerland's Foreign Ministry in Berne.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icrc.org/eng/resources/documents/news-release/2011/geneva-news-2011-10-19.htm |title=ICRC names new president |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Maurer was appointed Ambassador and Permanent Representative of Switzerland to the United Nations in New York. In this position, he endeavoured to integrate Switzerland, which had only recently joined the United Nations, into multilateral networks. In June 2009, the [[United Nations General Assembly]] elected Maurer Chairman of the [[United Nations General Assembly Fifth Committee|Fifth Committee]], in charge of United Nations administrative and budgetary affairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/press/en/2009/bio4129.doc.htm |title=Peter Maurer of Switzerland Chair of Fifth Committee |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2009}}</ref> In addition, he was elected Chairman of the Burundi Configuration of the [[Peacebuilding Commission|UN Peacebuilding Commission]]. In January 2010, Maurer became Switzerland's State Secretary for Foreign Affairs, a position he held until he was elected President of the ICRC.\n\nSince 2012, Maurer has led the ICRC through an historic budget increase, from 1.1 billion CHF in 2011 to over 1.6 billion CHF in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icrc.org/en/who-we-are/finances |title=ICRC Finances |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2015}}</ref> In addition, he launched the world\u2019s first \u201chumanitarian impact bond\u201d scheme, in which private investors lend \u20ac22 million of five-year funding and their repayments depend on what difference the project makes to its clients\u2019 lives.<ref>Kate Allen (September 8, 2017) [https://www.ft.com/content/8d82241d-096b-313e-91d8-786ba99d2073 Red Cross launches \u201chumanitarian impact bond\u201d] ''[[Financial Times]]''.</ref> Since 2019, Maurer has been co-chairing the [[World Economic Forum]] High-Level Group on Humanitarian Investing, alongside [[B\u00f8rge Brende]] and [[Kristalina Georgieva]].<ref>[https://www.weforum.org/press/2019/01/world-economic-forum-2019-annual-meeting-launching-a-new-humanitarian-investing-initiative/ World Economic Forum 2019 Annual Meeting launching a new Humanitarian Investing Initiative] [[World Economic Forum]], press release of January 18, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* [[International Gender Champions]] (IGC), Member (since 2017)<ref>[https://genderchampions.com/champions Members] [[International Gender Champions]] (IGC).</ref>\n* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Member of the Board (since 2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weforum.org/news/peter-maurer-joins-foundation-board-world-economic-forum |title=Peter Maurer Joins Foundation Board, World Economic Forum |accessdate=2015-05-08 |year=2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104114218/http://www.weforum.org/news/peter-maurer-joins-foundation-board-world-economic-forum |archivedate=4 November 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[World Economic Forum]] (WEF), Co-Chair of the Global Future Council on the Future of the Humanitarian System<ref>[https://www.weforum.org/communities/the-future-of-the-humanitarian-system Global Future Council: The Future of the Humanitarian System] [[World Economic Forum]].</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n* 2014 \u2013 Honorary doctorate, [[University of Basel]]<ref>[https://www.unibas.ch/en/News-Events/News/Uni-Info/Dies-Academicus-2014-at-the-University-of-Basel--Honorary-Doctorate-for-ICRC-President-Peter-Maurer.html Dies Academicus 2014 at the University of Basel: Honorary Doctorate for ICRC President Peter Maurer] [[University of Basel]], press release of November 28, 2014.</ref>\n* 2018 \u2013 Honorary doctorate, [[Waseda University]]<ref>[https://www.waseda.jp/top/en-news/62682 Honorary Doctorate Conferred on Dr. Peter Maurer, President of the International Committee of the Red Cross] [[Waseda University]], press release of December 7, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaurer is married and is the father of two children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n* UN, 15 September 2009. [https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2009/bio4129.doc.htm PETER MAURER OF SWITZERLAND CHAIR OF FIFTH COMMITTEE]\n* ICRC, 19 October 2011. [http://www.icrc.org/eng/resources/documents/n